We start by “picking out” from the hundreds of transactions those that represent operating expenditures (including depreciation) – that is, the rows whose “type” field shows any kind of Expense (for example “Sales Expenses”, “Administrative Expenses”, “Financial Expenses”) and also the “Depreciation” entry. (Other transactions such as Purchase, Sale, Fixed Assets, Initial deposits, Transfers, or even Interest Receivables are not “expenses” in the income‐statement sense.) 

Below is one way to proceed:

1. Identify the rows with a type that begins “Expense” (or is “Depreciation”). For example, in our table the rows we must include are the ones whose “type” equals “Sales Expenses”, “Administrative Expenses”, “Financial Expenses” and the one “Depreciation” row. (In our table there are many Expense rows.)  
2. Sum up the “amount” fields for those rows. (Make sure not to include transactions of type “Purchase”, “Sale”, “Fixed Assets …”, “Initial…”, “Transfer”, etc.)
